    <!-- Article Content -->
    <div class="article-content">
      <div class="article-body">

        <p class="lead">Commercial real estate purchase agreements in Arizona involve significant capital and complex terms. Understanding the key provisions—and potential pitfalls—can mean the difference between a smooth closing and a deal that falls apart at the last minute.</p>

        <p>At Camelback Law Group, we've negotiated hundreds of commercial purchase agreements across Arizona. Here are the issues that matter most.</p>

        <h2>1. Due Diligence Period: Your Window to Investigate</h2>

        <p>The due diligence period is arguably the most critical phase of any commercial real estate transaction. This is your opportunity to thoroughly investigate the property before committing to close.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <h4>Key Considerations:</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Length of period:</strong> 30-60 days is typical for commercial transactions, but complex properties may require more time</li>
            <li><strong>Extension rights:</strong> Negotiate automatic extensions for delays in receiving materials from the seller</li>
            <li><strong>Termination rights:</strong> Ensure you can terminate for any reason (or no reason) during the inspection period</li>
            <li><strong>Deposit at risk:</strong> Understand when your earnest money becomes non-refundable</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <p>Arizona courts generally enforce due diligence provisions as written, so precise drafting is essential. A vague termination right may not protect you if disputes arise.</p>

        <h2>2. Title and Survey Review</h2>

        <p>Title issues can derail a transaction or create long-term problems for property owners. Arizona's unique history—including Spanish land grants, mining claims, and water rights—can create title complications not found in other states.</p>

        <h3>Common Arizona Title Issues:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Easements for utilities, access, or drainage</li>
          <li>CC&Rs and deed restrictions that limit property use</li>
          <li>Mechanic's lien rights (Arizona has specific notice requirements)</li>
          <li>Water rights and assured water supply requirements</li>
          <li>Mineral rights reservations</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Your purchase agreement should give you adequate time to review the title commitment and survey, and clear mechanisms to object to unacceptable exceptions.</p>

        <h2>3. Representations and Warranties</h2>

        <p>Seller representations and warranties allocate risk between the parties. In Arizona commercial transactions, these provisions are heavily negotiated.</p>

        <div class="highlight-box">
          <h4>Critical Representations to Negotiate:</h4>
          <p><strong>Environmental:</strong> Has the property been used for industrial purposes? Any known contamination?</p>
          <p><strong>Litigation:</strong> Are there pending or threatened claims affecting the property?</p>
          <p><strong>Leases:</strong> Are all lease documents accurate and complete? Any tenant defaults?</p>
          <p><strong>Permits:</strong> Does the property have all required permits and approvals?</p>
          <p><strong>Compliance:</strong> Does the property comply with zoning, building codes, and ADA requirements?</p>
        </div>

        <p>Pay careful attention to survival periods—how long after closing can you bring a claim based on a breached representation? Arizona allows parties to contract for limited survival periods, which sellers typically prefer.</p>

        <h2>4. Closing Conditions and Mechanics</h2>

        <p>The path from signed contract to closed transaction involves numerous conditions and procedural requirements.</p>

        <h3>Arizona-Specific Considerations:</h3>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Escrow:</strong> Arizona typically uses title companies as escrow agents, not attorneys</li>
          <li><strong>Affidavit of Property Value:</strong> Required for all Arizona real estate transfers</li>
          <li><strong>FIRPTA:</strong> Foreign Investment in Real Property Tax Act withholding requirements</li>
          <li><strong>Prorations:</strong> Property taxes, HOA dues, and rents must be properly allocated</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>5. Default and Remedies</h2>

        <p>What happens if one party fails to perform? Arizona law provides default rules, but purchase agreements typically modify these significantly.</p>

        <div class="callout warning">
          <h4>Watch Out For:</h4>
          <ul>
            <li><strong>Liquidated damages:</strong> Limiting the seller's remedy to retention of the earnest money deposit</li>
            <li><strong>Specific performance:</strong> Ensuring buyers can force the sale if sellers breach</li>
            <li><strong>Notice and cure periods:</strong> How much time does a defaulting party have to fix the problem?</li>
            <li><strong>Attorney's fees:</strong> Arizona follows the "American Rule" unless the contract provides otherwise</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <h2>6. Financing Contingencies</h2>

        <p>If you're obtaining financing, the loan contingency is crucial. This provision should address:</p>

        <ul>
          <li>The type, amount, and terms of acceptable financing</li>
          <li>A deadline for loan commitment</li>
          <li>What constitutes an acceptable commitment letter</li>
          <li>Buyer's obligations to pursue financing diligently</li>
          <li>Consequences if financing is not obtained</li>
        </ul>

        <p>Sellers often push for tight financing deadlines and limited termination rights. Buyers need enough flexibility to secure appropriate financing without giving up deal certainty.</p>

        <h2>Protect Your Investment</h2>

        <p>Commercial real estate transactions involve significant risk and complexity. The purchase agreement is your primary tool for allocating that risk and protecting your investment.</p>

        <p>Whether you're a developer acquiring land, an investor purchasing an income property, or a business owner buying your facility, experienced legal counsel can help you negotiate terms that protect your interests while keeping the deal on track.</p>

        <div class="article-cta">
